  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the end of service benefits of an ex-president of the USA? How much is the ex-president\u2019s pension? How much is he paid in allowances?",
  "response": "The end of service benefits for former presidents of the United States are established by the Former Presidents Act (FPA) of 1958. Here's a detailed breakdown of these benefits:\n\n### Pension\n- **Annual Pension**: As of 2022, former presidents receive a yearly pension of $221,400. This amount is adjusted annually for cost-of-living increases.\n\n### Allowances and Benefits\n1. **Staff and Office Allowance**:\n   - Former presidents are provided with funds to maintain an office. The amount varies based on several factors, including the number of staff members and office expenses, but it can be up to $150,000 annually.\n\n2. **Travel Allowance**:\n   - They receive a travel allowance, which includes reimbursement for official travel expenses.\n\n3. **Medical and Health Insurance**:\n   - Former presidents and their spouses are provided with lifetime Secret Service protection and comprehensive health insurance. This benefit extends to their children until they reach the age of 16.\n\n4. **Secret Service Protection**:\n   - Former presidents are entitled to lifetime Secret Service protection. However, in 2013, this was amended to limit protection to 10 years for presidents inaugurated after January 1, 1997, unless extended by Congress.\n\n5. **Transition Expenses**:\n   - There is also funding provided to help with the transition out of office, which can include expenses related to moving and setting up a new office.\n\n### Additional Considerations\n- **Presidential Library**: While not a direct financial benefit to the former president, the federal government assists in the construction and maintenance of presidential libraries, which serve as repositories for historical records and can involve significant funding.\n\nThese benefits are intended to support former presidents in their post-presidency lives and ensure they can continue to serve the public in various capacities without financial strain.",
